```graph
digraph G {
    rankdir=LR;
    node [shape=box];

    Sensor -> ChargeAmp -> HighPassFilter -> Amplifier -> AntiAliasingFilter -> ADC;

    // Description of the blocks
    Sensor [label="Piezoelectric Accelerometer\n(Sensitivity: 100 pC/g)"];
    ChargeAmp [label="Charge Amplifier"];
    HighPassFilter [label="High-Pass Filter\n(Cutoff: 0.25 Hz)"];
    Amplifier [label="Voltage Amplifier\n(Gain: Set for 1 Vpp Output)"];
    AntiAliasingFilter [label="Anti-Aliasing Filter\n(Cutoff: <2 Hz)"];
    ADC [label="Analog-to-Digital Converter\n(If Required)"];
}
```

```Explanations
Sensor:
- The piezoelectric accelerometer is the sensing element that converts mechanical vibration into an electrical charge. The sensitivity of 100 pC/g is used to determine the output charge for a given acceleration.

ChargeAmp:
- The charge amplifier converts the charge output from the piezoelectric sensor into a voltage. Its design must take into account the expected range of charge generated by the sensor to ensure the output voltage is within the linear range of the amplifier. The charge amplifier will also set the low-frequency response of the system.

HighPassFilter:
- The high-pass filter ensures the system's low-frequency response is 3 dB down at 0.25 Hz, filtering out any DC offset and very low-frequency components that are not of interest. This is critical for accurate measurement of the target vibration frequency range.

Amplifier:
- The voltage amplifier adjusts the level of the signal from the charge amplifier to achieve the required 1 V peak-to-peak output. The gain of the amplifier is determined based on the maximum output of the charge amplifier and the desired output voltage.

AntiAliasingFilter:
- Used only if an ADC is part of the system, this anti-aliasing filter is placed before the ADC to remove any frequency components above half the sampling rate (Nyquist frequency), thus preventing aliasing when the analog signal is converted to digital.

ADC:
- An analog-to-digital converter is included if the system requires a digital output. The ADC samples the analog signal and converts it to a digital representation for further processing or display. The ADC is optional and may not be required if the output is strictly analog.
```

